  "prompt": "How has legislation evolved to combat money laundering?",
  "response": "Legislation against money laundering has evolved significantly over time, becoming increasingly comprehensive and sophisticated:\n\n1. Early Stages\n- Limited legal frameworks\n- Minimal international cooperation\n- Weak enforcement mechanisms\n- Primarily focused on drug-related financial crimes\n\n2. Key Milestones\n- Bank Secrecy Act (1970, USA)\n- First international anti-money laundering guidelines\n- Establishment of Financial Action Task Force (FATF) in 1989\n\n3. Modern Developments\n- Enhanced Know Your Customer (KYC) requirements\n- Mandatory reporting of suspicious transactions\n- Stricter penalties for non-compliance\n- Expanded scope beyond traditional banking\n- Digital currency and cryptocurrency regulations\n- International information sharing mechanisms\n\n4. Technological Adaptations\n- Advanced monitoring systems\n- Machine learning and AI for detection\n- Real-time transaction tracking\n- Enhanced digital verification processes\n\n5. Global Collaboration\n- Standardized international regulations\n- Cross-border information exchange\n- Coordinated enforcement efforts\n- Uniform compliance standards\n\n6. Emerging Trends\n- Cryptocurrency regulations\n- Blockchain tracking\n- Enhanced cybersecurity measures\n- Continuous regulatory adaptation\n\nThis evolution reflects increasing complexity in financial systems and ongoing efforts to prevent financial crimes.",
